. You wouldn\u0027t even bother arguing unless you assumed the Universe/gods *are* fundamentally good and just. And if they *are*, then they wouldn\u0027t let any part of their system be totally screwed up without reason. So chill, accept it.\n\n**6. Practice What Sucks.**\n*Original:* Practice things you despair of achieving. Left hand, slow from lack of practice, holds bridle stronger than right because practised.\n*Bro Version:* Even the stuff you think you totally suck at – practice it. Your left hand might be clumsy for most things \u0027cause you don\u0027t use it, but it probably holds the reins tighter than your right \u0027cause it\u0027s gotten practice *at that specific thing*. Train even your weak spots.\n\n**7. Deathbed Reality Check.**\n*Original:* What should body/soul be like when death comes? Brevity of life, gulf of time, weakness of matter.\n*Bro Version:* Think about it: When death catches up, what state should your body and mind be in? Remember how short life is, how huge eternity before and after is, and how flimsy all physical stuff really is.\n\n**8. Strip It Bare.**\n*Original:* Consider causes stripped of covering; relations of actions; nature of pain, pleasure, death, fame; who causes own unrest; how none hindered by neighbour; all things are judgment.\n*Bro Version:* Look at the raw causes of things, naked, without the usual BS layers. Understand the connections between your actions. Get real about pain, pleasure, death, fame. Realize *you* are the source of your own stress. Nobody else can truly block *you* (your mind). Everything is how you judge it.\n\n**9. Boxer, Not Gladiator.**\n*Original:* Use principles like a boxer, not gladiator. Gladiator drops/picks up sword. Boxer\u0027s hand is always ready, just needs clenching.\n*Bro Version:* Handle your principles like a boxer, not a swordsman. The gladiator puts his weapon down, picks it up. The boxer\u0027s weapon – his fist – is always *part of him*, ready to go. He just needs to clen